Do not use textContent to get inner textAccording to specification, textContent includes everything in thentarget's children, including script and style tags.[1] Even jQuerynrecognise that using it in their .text() implementation is a bug,nalthough they (FWIW) refuse to fix it.[2]nnOther options, most importantly using innerText instead, also haventheir own set of problems, as described in a relevant Mozillandocument.[3]nnThe current implementation ditches all the above. We now traversenchild nodes ourselves, and implement custom logic to explicitlynexclude SCRIPT and STYLE tags.nnThis should behave very similarly to textContent except for SCRIPTnand STYLE tags. Anything that does not conform to specification ofntextContent should be considered as a bug.nn[1]: http://www.w3.org/TR/DOM-Level-3-Core/core.html#Node3-textContentn[2]: http://bugs.jquery.com/ticket/8111n[3]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Node.textContentn

Dynamically replace content instead of reloadingThis works around the WebView caching problem. By reusing the same DOMnas much as possible, we can avoid reloading external resources againnand again every time we render. This should improve performance onnlarge documents.nnNote that the current implementation is quite crude. We always get thenwhole HTML document, and extract the part we need after putting thenwhole thing together (using regex). Ideally, since the style and scriptnsection never updates during document editing, and the main contentnnever updates on pref changes, we should be able to only notify changesnfor needed parts seperately. But we lack that kind of renderernnotification. This would be a target for refactoring in the future.n
